The paper deals with proximity graphs, which are commonly used in computational geometry (cs.CG) and graph drawing (cs.GR). The introduction of witness graphs as a generalization of proximity graphs makes it relevant to data structures (cs.DS) and discrete mathematics (cs.DM). The paper also discusses point set discrimination, which is a problem in machine learning and pattern recognition, making it relevant to social and information sciences (cs.SI).
